div.cell {

  display: -webkit-box;

}

}

.prompt {
  /* This needs to be wide enough for 3 digit prompt numbers: In[100]: */
  min-width: 14ex;

  margin: 0px;
  font-family: monospace;
  text-align: right;

  -moz-user-select: none;
  -ms-user-select: none;

}

/* The following gets added to the <head> if it is detected that the user has a
 * monospace font with inconsistent normal/bold/italic height.  See
 * notebookmain.js.  Such fonts will have keywords vertically offset with
 * respect to the rest of the text.  The user should select a better font.
 * See: https://github.com/ipython/ipython/issues/1503
 *
 * .CodeMirror span {
 *      vertical-align: bottom;
 * }
 */
.CodeMirror {
  line-height: 1.21429em;
  /* Changed from 1em to our global default */
  font-size: 14px;
  height: auto;
  /* Changed to auto to autogrow */
  background: none;
  /* Changed from white to allow our bg to show through */
}
.CodeMirror-scroll {
  /*  The CodeMirror docs are a bit fuzzy on if overflow-y should be hidden or visible.*/
  /*  We have found that if it is visible, vertical scrollbars appear with font size changes.*/
  overflow-y: hidden;
  overflow-x: auto;
}
.CodeMirror-lines {
  /* In CM2, this used to be 0.4em, but in CM3 it went to 4px. We need the em value because */
  /* we have set a different line-height and want this to scale with that. */
  /* Note that this should set vertical padding only, since CodeMirror assumes
       that horizontal padding will be set on CodeMirror pre */
  padding: 0.4em 0;
}
.CodeMirror-linenumber {
  padding: 0 8px 0 4px;
}
.CodeMirror-gutters {
  border-bottom-left-radius: 2px;
  border-top-left-radius: 2px;
}
.CodeMirror pre {
  /* In CM3 this went to 4px from 0 in CM2. This sets horizontal padding only,
    use .CodeMirror-lines for vertical */
  padding: 0 0.4em;
  border: 0;
  border-radius: 0;
}
.CodeMirror-cursor {
  border-left: 1.4px solid black;
}
@media screen and (min-width: 2138px) and (max-width: 4319px) {

    border-left: 2px solid black;
  }
}

</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p><strong>Correlation</strong>: corr() shows tha changes according to each other. Shows us a correlation matrix. Each coefficent in correlation matrix is between <strong>-1 and +1</strong></p>
<p><strong>+1 means</strong> that there is perfect dorrelation between these two sets. If one is increases the other increases at the same time with same percentage.</p>
<p><strong>0 means</strong> that there is no correlation</p>
<p><strong>-1 means</strong> that there is perfect negative correlation. If the one is increases the other decreases at the same time and same percentage.</p>
</div>

entry.content:
Introduction

PyTorch is a automatic differentiation and gpu computation tool and also one of the most popular deep learning framewoks.

I will build very simple linear regression model with both PyTorch and pure Python and try to indicate pure Python equivalents of the PyTorch code.

Linear Regression with PyTorch

Lets consider our dataset is x=[2,3,4]; y=[6,9,12] and our hypothesis function is y=x*w Then ultimate situation w would be 3.

Lets begin the iteration with w=1

If we ignore activation function just in this case, our gradiant will be:

\(\frac{\delta L}{\delta w} = \frac{\delta{s}^{2}}{\delta \hat{y}}*\frac{\delta (x*w)}{\delta w}\) and \(s=\hat{y}-y\)

Then for the first sample, which is x=2;y=6, gradient will be

gradient: \(2*s*x=2*(\hat{y}-y)*x=2*(x*w-y)*x=2*((2*1)-6)*2=-8\)

For second sample; -36

For third sample; -64

Pure Python code of this

x_data = [2.0, 3.0, 4.0]
y_data = [6.0, 9.0, 12.0]

w = 1.0  # a random guess: random value

# our model forward pass


def forward(x):
    return x * w


# Loss function
def loss(x, y):
    y_pred = forward(x)
    return (y_pred - y) * (y_pred - y)


# we define the gradient here manually, but usually calculating gradients and applying them in chain rule is not so handy
# therefore we will use backward method of PyTorch in next example
def gradient(x, y):  # d_loss/d_w
    return 2 * x * (x * w - y)

# Before training
print("predict (before training)",  "for x=5, y=", forward(5))

# Training loop with Stochastic Gradient Descent
# We are updating w values for every sample for each epochs
# it converges fast but fluctuates too much also. 
# we would prefer mini-batch gradient descent in bigger datasets.
for epoch in range(10):
    for x_val, y_val in zip(x_data, y_data):
        grad = gradient(x_val, y_val)
        w = w - 0.01 * grad
        print("\tgrad: ", x_val, y_val, round(grad, 2))
        l = loss(x_val, y_val)

    print("progress:", epoch, "w=", round(w, 2), "loss=", round(l, 2))

# After training
print("predict (after training)",  "for x=5, y=", forward(5))

Autograd Version

import torch
from torch.autograd import Variable
x_data = [2.0, 3.0, 4.0]
y_data = [6.0, 9.0, 12.0]

w = Variable(torch.Tensor([1.0]),  requires_grad=True)  # Any random value

# our model forward pass


def forward(x):
    return x * w

# Loss function


def loss(x, y):
    y_pred = forward(x)
    return (y_pred - y) * (y_pred - y)

# Before training
print("predict (before training)",  5, forward(5).data[0])

# Training loop
for epoch in range(10):
    for x_val, y_val in zip(x_data, y_data):
        l = loss(x_val, y_val)
        # backward method accessible because of definition of w is Variable()
        # and it calculates all partial derivatives w.r.t all Variables who has requires_grad=True parameter
        l.backward()
        # .data[0] is raw value
        print("\tgrad: ", x_val, y_val, w.grad.data[0])
        # w.grad.data is tensor value
        w.data = w.data - 0.01 * w.grad.data

        # Manually zero the gradients after updating weights
        w.grad.data.zero_()

    print("progress:", epoch, l.data[0])

# After training
print("predict (after training)",  5, forward(5).data[0])

In PyTorch Way

import torch
from torch.autograd import Variable

x_data = Variable(torch.Tensor([[2.0], [3.0], [4.0]]))
y_data = Variable(torch.Tensor([[6.0], [9.0], [12.0]]))

###################
# DESIGN YOUR  MODEL
###################
class Model(torch.nn.Module):

    def __init__(self):
        """
        In the constructor we instantiate two nn.Linear module
        """
        super(Model, self).__init__()
        self.linear = torch.nn.Linear(1, 1)  # One in and one out

    def forward(self, x):
        """
        In the forward function we accept a Variable of input data and we must return
        a Variable of output data. We can use Modules defined in the constructor as
        well as arbitrary operators on Variables.
        """
        y_pred = self.linear(x)
        return y_pred

# our model
model = Model()

##############################
# CONSTRUCT LOSS AND OPTIMIZER. 
# The call to model.parameters()
# in the SGD constructor will contain the learnable parameters of the two
# nn.Linear modules which are members of the model.
criterion = torch.nn.MSELoss(size_average=False)
#updates model.parameters() which is weights
optimizer = torch.optim.SGD(model.parameters(), lr=0.01)

#############################
# TRAINING CYCLE
# FORWARD-BACKWARD and UPDATE
for epoch in range(10):
    # Forward pass: Compute predicted y by passing x to the model by initial random weights
    y_pred = model(x_data)

    # Compute and print loss
    loss = criterion(y_pred, y_data)
    print(epoch, loss.data[0])

    # Zero gradients initializes them
    optimizer.zero_grad()
    # perform a backward pass
    loss.backward()
    #and update the weights
    optimizer.step()


# After training
hour_var = Variable(torch.Tensor([[5.0]]))
y_pred = model(hour_var)
print("predict (after training)",  5, model(hour_var).data[0][0])

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>We need to get smoothened this wheezy graph by getting moving average.</p>
<p><strong>Moving 25 average:</strong> Gets 25 points before this point and calculates the average. Then goes next point and calculates average of 25 previous points again. Then goes next point and calculates average of 25 previous points. Then do this again...</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [23]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class="highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># makes df sorted according to index (datetime)</span>
<span class="n">albany_df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sort_index</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">inplace</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<h4 id="I-want-to-graph-all-the-regions-not-only-Albany-on-one-chart.-How-am-i-going-to-do-it?">I want to graph all the regions not only Albany on one chart. How am i going to do it?<a class="anchor-link" href="#I-want-to-graph-all-the-regions-not-only-Albany-on-one-chart.-How-am-i-going-to-do-it?">¶</a></h4><p>We can get moving averages of all regions in different dataframes and add them in a loop. But the best practice is restructuring the dataframe and ploting them in a single plot method without a loop.</p>
<p>So we will restructure the df as the column names would be regions and rows would be price25a.</p>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [29]:</div>

<div class="input_area">
<div class="highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># getting unique list of regions</span>
<span class="nb">list</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nb">set</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nb">list</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">"region"</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">values</span><span class="p">)))</span>
</pre></div>

</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [35]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class="highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">graph_df</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">region</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'region'</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">unique</span><span class="p">()[:</span><span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">]:</span>
    <span class="n">region_df</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">copy</span><span class="p">()[</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'region'</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">==</span><span class="n">region</span><span class="p">]</span>
    <span class="n">region_df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_index</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Date'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">inplace</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">region_df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sort_index</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">inplace</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">region_df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">f</span><span class="s2">"</span><span class="si">{region}</span><span class="s2">_price25ma"</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">region_df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">"AveragePrice"</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">rolling</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">25</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mean</span><span class="p">()</span>
    <span class="n">region_df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">dropna</span><span class="p">()</span>

    <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">graph_df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">empty</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="n">graph_df</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">region_df</span><span class="p">[[</span><span class="n">f</span><span class="s2">"</span><span class="si">{region}</span><span class="s2">_price25ma"</span><span class="p">]]</span>  <span class="c1"># note the double square brackets! (so df rather than series)</span>
    <span class="k">else</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="n">graph_df</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">graph_df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">join</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">region_df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">f</span><span class="s2">"</span><span class="si">{region}</span><span class="s2">_price25ma"</span><span class="p">])</span>

<span class="n">graph_df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">tail</span><span class="p">()</span> 
</pre></div>
